TITLE: Walmart Anticipates a Store Manager Shortage Despite $200,000-a-Year Pay
SUMMARY: Many managers leading the company’s roughly 4,700 U.S. stores have been in their roles for at least a decade, and Walmart executives say they need to find a new generation to replace them.

TITLE: Russian Invasion Intensifies Role of New U.S.-EU Tech Council
SUMMARY: The U.S.-EU Trade and Technology Council had its first meeting in Pittsburgh last fall, which participants said helped forge ties that proved critical when the two economies joined to impose sanctions on the Kremlin following its Feb. 24 attack on Ukraine.

TITLE: Behind Fake-Account Issue That Musk Cited in Calling Twitter Deal 'On Hold'
SUMMARY: Social media has grappled with phony accounts for years, raising questions about why Tesla CEO Elon Musk is talking about them again now.

TITLE: Borrowing Costs Balloon as Home Construction Gets Delayed
SUMMARY: People who agreed to buy homes under construction but haven’t yet closed are facing mortgage-interest rates that could be nearly double what they anticipated.

TITLE: The Dollar Is Winning in a Messy Global Economy---and That Matters in the Fight Against Inflation
SUMMARY: A stronger U.S. dollar could help the Federal Reserve hold down the cost of imported goods.

TITLE: CEO Pay Packages Rose to $14.7 Million in 2021, a New High
SUMMARY: Stock awards pushed median compensation to a sixth-straight record, and nine CEOs got packages of $50 million or more.

TITLE: Saudi Aramco Posts Record Quarterly Profit on Surging Oil Prices
SUMMARY: The oil giant said its net income surged 82% to $39.5 billion in the first three months of 2022 as it benefits from surging energy prices following Russia’s invasion of Ukraine.

TITLE: Nations Aim to Secure Supply Chains by Turning Offshoring Into 'Friend-Shoring'
SUMMARY: U.S. officials and allies around the world are looking to establish friendly supply routes for key goods amid a war and global pandemic.

TITLE: Baby Formula Shortage Draws Stepped Up Response From Biden, Democrats
SUMMARY: House Democrats plan to fast-track a vote on relaxing regulations for baby formula provided under the WIC federal nutrition program in an effort to boost availability.

TITLE: Inflation Is Headed Lower---but Maybe Not Low Enough
SUMMARY: While supply disruptions are subsiding, without slower demand, inflation will still be too high for the Fed’s comfort to stop raising interest rates.

TITLE: Why It's So Hard to Keep Russian Diamonds and Gold Out of the U.S. Despite Sanctions
SUMMARY: Jewelers and officials are urged to stem the flow of Russian gems and precious metals likely still entering the U.S.

TITLE: The Biggest Problem With Flying Cars Is on the Ground
SUMMARY: Whether you call them eVTOLs, “flying cars” or air taxis, these all-electric, vertical take-off-and-landing passenger vehicles promise to make George Jetson’s commute a reality—if only their manufacturers can figure out where to land them.

TITLE: Used-Car Buyers Are Seeing Relief on Once-Soaring Prices
SUMMARY: Buyers challenged by high used car prices are sitting on the sidelines, driving down demand and prices in the pre-owned market.

TITLE: Ford Unloads More Shares of Electric-Vehicle Startup Rivian
SUMMARY: Ford sold 7 million Rivian shares at a price of $26.88, the company says. That followed an 8-million-share sale earlier in the week at about the same price.

TITLE: At Tech Companies, the Rebellion Against the Return to the Office Is Getting Serious
SUMMARY: Some of the economy’s most in-demand employees are about to find out how much power they have over where and how they do their jobs.

TITLE: Chinese Wind-Turbine Companies Seek Global Growth as Western Rivals Struggle
SUMMARY: Companies such as Ming Yang and Goldwind are expanding internationally as GE, Vestas face headwinds due to rising materials costs and supply-chain bottlenecks.

TITLE: TikTok Is Eating Up Rivals. Can It Keep Users Hooked?
SUMMARY: The app capitalized on consumers’ bite-sized attention span. Now rivals are competing for the same eyeballs.
